      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-gray-900">Standing Desk Guide: Manual vs Electric vs Converter — Which to Buy?</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-8 text-gray-600">
        I used a standing desk for three years, then switched back to a fixed desk. Here is what I learned about which type is actually worth buying — and who should skip them entirely.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-10 prose prose-lg prose-gray max-w-none">

        <p>Standing desks have gone from niche ergonomic accessory to mainstream office furniture in about a decade. The marketing makes bold claims: prevents heart disease, fixes back pain, adds years to your life. The reality is more nuanced. But there is also real benefit here — if you use the desk correctly, and if you buy the right type for how you actually work.</p>

        <h2>What the research actually says</h2>

        <p>The data on standing desks is weaker than the marketing would have you believe. A 2018 Cochrane systematic review — the gold standard for medical evidence — analyzed 20 studies on sit-stand desks and found they reduced sitting time by about 84 minutes per workday on average. But the evidence for long-term health benefits like reduced heart disease or lower mortality was rated "low quality."</p>

        <p>That does not mean standing desks are useless. It means the benefit comes from <em>moving more</em> and <em>sitting less</em> — not from standing still instead of sitting still. Standing in one place for hours causes its own problems: varicose veins, foot pain, lower back fatigue. The healthy behavior is changing positions throughout the day, not picking one position and staying in it.</p>

        <p>This is actually good news, because it means you do not need to stand for hours to get the benefit. Alternating between sitting and standing a few times per day — even just 15-20 minutes of standing per hour — is enough.</p>

        <h2>The three types, honestly compared</h2>

        <h3>Desktop converters ($80-300)</h3>

        <p>A converter sits on top of your existing desk. You raise it to stand, lower it to sit. No need to replace your desk, which makes this the cheapest and most renter-friendly option.</p>

        <p>The VariDesk Pro Plus 36 ($300) is the one I see in every coworking space and home office tour. It uses a spring-assisted lift — you squeeze a lever and the whole thing rises smoothly. No motor means nothing to break, and the spring mechanism has been refined over years of iterations. At 36 inches wide, it fits dual monitors comfortably.</p>

        <p>The downsides: converters eat up a significant chunk of your desk surface even when lowered — they sit about 4-6 inches tall in the lowered position. And the keyboard tray on the VariDesk sits a few inches above your actual desk surface, which can create an awkward typing height when sitting if your chair does not adjust high enough. Measure before buying.</p>

        <p>Cheaper converters ($80-150) use a manual lift with no spring assist — you physically lift the weight of your monitors every time you want to stand. These work, but the friction means you will stand less. After a few weeks, most people stop bothering. If you go the converter route, spring-assisted or gas-spring lift is worth the extra money.</p>

        <h3>Manual crank desks ($150-400)</h3>

        <p>A hand crank adjusts the desk height. No motor, no electronics, nothing that can fail. This is both the main advantage and the main disadvantage — cranking takes 30-60 seconds each time you switch positions, and that delay is enough friction that most people stand less than they intend to.</p>

        <p>The IKEA Mittzon ($290) is IKEA's manual standing desk and it is... fine. The crank mechanism is smoother than you would expect, the desk is stable at height, and assembly is standard IKEA (frustrating but doable). For the price, it is solid. But I would only recommend a manual crank if you genuinely plan to stand once or twice a day at most, or if your desk is positioned somewhere without access to a power outlet.</p>

        <h3>Electric standing desks ($250-3,000+)</h3>

        <p>Press a button, the desk moves. Two memory presets save your sitting and standing heights. The convenience of electric adjustment means you will actually change positions throughout the day — which is the entire point of having a standing desk in the first place.</p>

        <p>The Flexispot EC1 ($250-300) is the entry-level electric desk I recommend. Single motor, two presets, 55-inch top, smooth operation. It is not fancy — the laminate is basic, the motor is a bit noisier than premium desks, and there is no collision detection. But it does the thing: it goes up and down reliably, and at $250-300 it is accessible to most people.</p>

        <p>The Uplift V2 ($600-800) is the premium pick. Dual motors, significantly more stable at standing height, and massive customization — dozens of desktop materials and sizes, plus accessories like casters, monitor arms, cable trays, and a weird but popular under-desk hammock. The 15-year warranty is outstanding. If you have the budget and want a desk you will never need to replace, this is the one.</p>

        <p>The Herman Miller Nevi ($2,000+) is beautiful overkill. Silent motors, flawless fit and finish, and a price tag that would buy a used Honda Civic. Unless your employer is paying, skip it.</p>

        <h2>Stability: what you actually notice</h2>

        <p>All standing desks wobble slightly at standing height. The question is how much — and whether it bothers you.</p>

        <p>Single-motor desks (like the Flexispot EC1) have more wobble at full standing height, especially if you type heavily or lean on the desk. For most people doing standard office work, it is not a problem — the monitor shake is barely perceptible. But if you do anything that involves physical pressure on the desk — drawing, soldering, assembling things — the wobble will annoy you.</p>

        <p>Dual-motor desks are more stable because the weight is distributed across two lift columns. The Uplift V2 with the crossbar option is the most stable standing desk I have used under $1,000. At standing height, there is a slight monitor wobble when typing aggressively but nothing distracting.</p>

        <p>Four-leg desks are the most stable by far — they are basically tables that happen to go up and down — but they start at around $1,500 and are overkill for almost everyone.</p>

        <h2>The honest bottom line</h2>

        <p>If you are on a budget under $200: skip the standing desk entirely. Put that money toward a better chair. A good chair helps you every minute you are sitting; a standing desk only helps during the minutes you are standing.</p>

        <p>If you have $250-300 and want to stand: get the Flexispot EC1 electric desk. The electric adjustment means you will actually use it. Manual crank desks save you $100 upfront but you will stand less — and the whole point is to stand more.</p>

        <p>If you already have a desk you like: get a spring-assisted converter like the VariDesk Pro Plus 36. It preserves your current desk investment and gives you 90% of the standing desk experience.</p>

        <p>If you have $600-800 and want the last desk you will ever buy: Uplift V2. Customize it how you want, enjoy the stability and the 15-year warranty, and stop thinking about desks.</p>

        <p>After you get your desk set up, use our <a href="/tools/ergonomic-calculator/">Ergonomic Calculator</a> to find the right sitting and standing heights for your body.</p>
